@ejhumphrey I know I can use tempfiles, it's [in my first comment on this issue](https://github.com/rabitt/pysox/issues/27#issue-18574998) ;)

> @justinsalamon totally agree that pysox should throw an error if input_filepath = output_filepath, rather than creating an empty file. Didn't realize that was the main issue you were bringing up - I thought you wanted to be able to allow the paths to be the same.

@rabitt yes, the main issue I was bringing up is that the creation of an empty file is bad. However, my preferred solution would be for pysox to do use tempfiles (as per my example) to basically yes support using the same path for input/output. An alternative solution is what you propose (raise an error), which would be better than the current behavior, though I don't see why you wouldn't want to support overwriting the input file - there are plenty of tools out there (e.g. shutil, librosa) that happily overwrite files and it's a fairly common use case.

That's actually how it currently works, it protects any custom methods (and built-ins) from being overwritten. The issue is I think 'json' and 'yaml' are going to be popular keys, and I don't want to limit people from having them in their Box. Whereas it is a lot less likely for an incoming dictionary to have a 'to_yaml' or 'to_json' key. 

The second reason is that other libraries already have similarly named functions, so it makes it more common across tools. Such as `addict`'s [to_dict()](https://github.com/mewwts/addict#recursive-fallback-to-dict) and `Bunch`'s [to_yaml()](https://github.com/dsc/bunch/blob/master/bunch/__init__.py#L351).

So I am pretty set on keeping it as is for now. However it is always possible to subclass and have your own version that will act that way. 

```python

class MyBox(Box):

    def __init__(self, *args, **kwargs):
        self._protected_keys += ['json', 'yaml', 'csv']
        super(MyBox, self).__init__(*args, **kwargs)

    @property
    def json(self):
        return json.dumps(self.to_dict())

    ...
```

Also thanks for the `to_csv` idea, I opened it's own issue to track at https://github.com/cdgriffith/Box/issues/11

@satra, this is unintended. It is caused by the conversion from the value of a `Literal` into string below:
```python
class Literal(object):
    def __init__(self, value, datatype=None, langtag=None):
        self._value = six.text_type(value)  # value is always a string
```
I'm not sure there is a good solution for this, unless the equality check of `Literal` understands XSD values.

This is clearly undesirable. However, I'm reluctant to implement the handling of XSD types in equality check, which might be time-consuming.

I wonder if there is a simple solution.

