@stefanv @soupault Agreed, I am definitely not a fan of testing via setting random seeds. I think the best way to go about doing this is to completely forgo random seeds and instead to take in a random generator. This random generator must comply with a certain abstractions so that it can be used in the function.

The advantages are twofold – not only would users have the option of using their preferred RNGs, but it allows us to pass in a dummy/mock RNG for testing. This grants us absolute control over the parameters, allowing us to make more specific tests, and test if the function itself handles our numbers properly.

However, this would have the downside of making it more difficult for someone to just set the random seed without customizing everything – although I can't imagine why someone would need such a narrow scope of control in the first place.

